1466 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL / ROSS NEWHAN; DUNSTON MIGHT BE READY TO RECLAIM SPOT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROSS NEWHAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The depth chart on Manager Tom Trebelhorn's office wall at the Chicago Cubs' 
spring stadium lists four shortstops. 
</P>
<P>
 Two, Jose Vizcaino and Rey Sanchez, have done most of the playing for the Cubs 
during the last two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
 A third, Jose Hernandez, is an insurance policy formerly of the Texas Ranger 
and Cleveland Indian organizations, still young enough at 24 to generate 
interest among scouts. 
</P>
<P>
 The fourth name is that of Shawon Dunston, who had a herniated disk removed 
from his back on May 13, 1992, and hasn't played regularly since the previous 
September. 
</P>
<P>
 Now, however, he might be ready to become more than a name on the wall. 
</P>
<P>
 "There aren't four shortstops," Dunston said. "I'm the only one. I know I can 
play. I know I can be the best again." 
</P>
<P>
 That's what the Cubs are hoping, too. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're talking about a phenomenal talent," Trebelhorn said. "If he's healthy, 
he'll be the opening-day shortstop, and right now he's ahead of the timetable I 
had for him. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're very happy where he is, but knowledgeable it can change quickly. He 
seems to have total freedom, but how will (his back) respond when we get back 
to the cold in April?" 
</P>
<P>
 Dunston played 18 games before the surgery in 1992 and seven games last 
September. It has taken two years for him to feel he is prepared to play at his 
previous level. 
</P>
<P>
 He knew, he said, that when Darryl Strawberry tried to come back from a 
similar operation after only a half-year of therapy last year, it wouldn't 
work. And, indeed, Strawberry gave up after 32 games. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's been a learning experience," Dunston said. 
</P>
<P>
 "I do want to play, but I'm prepared to walk away. I won't make a fool of 
myself. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'd miss the game, but my role as a parent is worth more than the money and 
more than the game. 
</P>
<P>
 'I believe I'm a better person now and can be a better player because of it." 
</P>
<P>
 Dunston suspects he injured his back lifting daughter Whitnie from a car seat. 
He played in pain even in 1991, he said, but neither the back nor the game will 
get in the way of his responsibilities as a father. 
</P>
<P>
 At his home in Fremont, Calif., during the winter, Dunston said he would get 
up at 4 a.m. to do three hours of therapy -- swimming, stretching and weights 
-- so that he could be done in time to drive Whitnie and her sister, Jasmine, 
to school. 
</P>
<P>
 He attended PTA meetings and romped with 18-month-old Shawon Jr. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's been tough," Dunston said of the long recovery. "Some days you feel you 
can do anything in the world, the next day nothing. If I have my health, they 
can take the money." 
</P>
<P>
 Dunston signed a four-year, $12-million contract before the '92 season. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's easy to sleep, knowing if I have to retire I'll be able to take care of 
my family," he said, "but the Cubs have been great to me and I want to come 
back and repay them, show my appreciation." 
</P>
<P>
 Dunston, 31, and the Cubs believe he is through the worst. He homered in his 
first exhibition at-bat, beat out a pair of infield grounders the other day and 
has been playing consecutive games. 
</P>
<P>
 His potential return obviously strengthens the Cubs' depth and bargaining 
position. Both Vizcaino, a former Dodger who batted .287 in 151 games last 
year, and Sanchez would become valuable commodities.  
</P>
<P>
 Of Vizcaino, a switch-hitter who can play three infield positions and the 
outfield, Trebelhorn said: "He may be the best in baseball for what he brings 
to a club. His versatility becomes a terrific asset (if Dunston is playing 
regularly). I can't make the world perfect for everybody, but my job will be to 
see that they all stay ready." 
</P>
<P>
 He nodded at the chart on the wall and smiled. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 A former teacher in the Portland school system, Trebelhorn was asked what 
lessons he had learned managing the Milwaukee Brewers for six seasons. He was 
25 games over .500 during that stint, but his authority often was tested by 
players who thought he was too soft and had two sets of rules. 
</P>
<P>
 "You can't keep everybody happy, you can't do it all yourself and I have to 
make sure everybody understands what I'm doing," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 "I have a tendency for my mind to get ahead of my mouth, so I have to slow it 
down a bit." 
</P>
<P>
 In the long-suffering world of the Cubs, Trebelhorn succeeded Jim Lefebvre, 
despite pleas by Ryne Sandberg, Mark Grace and others to retain Lefebvre for 
the sake of continuity. 
</P>
<P>
 Every Cub manager inherits hefty historical baggage, but Trebelhorn, the 44th, 
said: 
</P>
<P>
 "I have nothing to do with the 43 who preceded me or the decades that preceded 
me. We've changed coaches, personnel, uniforms and divisions. It's part of the 
business, but I think we're comfortable and I think we're together on what 
we're trying to accomplish. 
</P>
<P>
 "We want to rebuild the mind set here. We have a good club. I want it to go 
out expecting to win. I don't want it hoping to win, but expecting to win." 
</P>
<P>
 Easy to say, harder to do. Still, the Cubs finished over .500 for only the 
third time since 1972 last season, despite the loss of free agents Greg Maddux 
and Andre Dawson, an injury that sidelined Sandberg for two months, the 
inability of former Dodger Mike Morgan (10-15) to fill Maddux's No. 1 berth in 
the rotation, an outfield that didn't need the Wrigley Field wind to have 
trouble catching balls and soap opera bickering between Lefebvre and General 
Manager Larry Himes. 
</P>
<P>
 The "Save Lefebvre" push by Grace and Sandberg might have contributed to 20 
victories in the last 28 games, but it didn't save Lefebvre. 
</P>
<P>
 Trebelhorn must fight the perception that he helped undermine Lefebvre during 
two years as a Cub coach. 
</P>
<P>
 He didn't grow in stature over the winter when he provided fodder for Chicago 
columnists and comedians with his response to a question on the psychological 
test Himes required of managerial candidates. 
</P>
<P>
 The question: "If you were a tree, what kind of a tree would you be?" 
Trebelhorn's answer: "A Cubs tree." 
</P>
<P>
 An oak or redwood, something perceived as hearty and strong, might have been 
the more suitable response, not a tree that wilts every summer. Nevertheless, 
Trebelhorn got the nod over Tony Muser, now on his coaching staff and viewed as 
a powerhouse successor if Trebelhorn and the Cubs stumble out of the gate. 
</P>
<P>
 In the meantime, trying to build that expectation of winning, Trebelhorn said 
the following is essential for the Cubs to contend in the National League's 
Central division: 
</P>
<P>
 -- The blossoming of career minor leaguer Karl Rhodes as a major league center 
fielder. 
</P>
<P>
 -- The bona fide arrival of Yorba Linda's Steve Trachsel as the No. 4 starter 
and a successful search for the No. 5. 
</P>
<P>
 -- The physical soundness of an infield that could be baseball's best: Grace, 
Sandberg, Dunston, Steve Buechele and Rick Wilkins. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 -- Former commissioner Fay Vincent displayed the extent of his bitterness at 
being forced from office in his 40-page book proposal that reduces Vincent to 
name-calling and sheds the stately and literate image he and the late Bart 
Giamatti espoused. 
</P>
<P>
 In his attack on the owners, Vincent described Peter O'Malley of the Dodgers 
as a "nitwit and bigot" and said that Jackie Autry of the Angels was 
"mean-spirited and not bright." 
</P>
<P>
 O'Malley declined comment. Autry would only say she was disappointed. So were 
many who thought Vincent got a bad deal, but expected him to keep it on a 
higher level. 
</P>
<P>
 -- The decision by Senate majority leader George Mitchell (D-Maine) not to 
seek reelection moves him to the forefront of commissioner candidates. 
</P>
<P>
 Timing is everything, and Mitchell would not be available until the fall, when 
the owners will have a better grasp on the status of labor talks and could be 
ready to appoint a commissioner. 
</P>
<P>
 -- While shredding the Major League Scouting Bureau in a cost-cutting move and 
reducing the umpire developmental fund by $1 million, owners have also rewarded 
interim commissioner Bud Selig with a $1 million salary bonus, showing they 
have their priorities in order as usual. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Hallelujah! The Michael Jordan circus is thought to be heading into its 
final week. A decision by the Chicago White Sox is expected no later than 
Sunday. The Jordan experiment spits on all those scouts who spend hours 
tracking college and high school players with far more baseball talent than 
Jordan but never even get the rookie league chance Jordan is receiving at the 
major league level. Jordan got his chance simply because he was outstanding in 
another sport and White Sox owner Jerry Reinsdorf, who also owns the Bulls, 
wanted to show his gratitude. 
</P>
<P>
 -- The theory was that Asians were too small and too frail to do more than 
pitch with finesse, not strong enough to pitch in the majors with consistent 
success. So much for stereotypes. The Dodgers' Chan Ho Park of Korea and the 
Seattle Mariners' teen-ager, Makoto Suzuki of Japan, are lighting up spring 
speed guns and might be the two hardest throwers in baseball. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
