<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LAGUNA HILLS; CHP TO LOOK AT SHERIFF'S UNIT CRASH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Authorities are investigating a collision Tuesday morning) between an Orange 
County sheriff's patrol unit that was on its way to an accident and a vehicle 
driven by an 86-year-old woman. 
</P>
<P>
 Both sheriff's Sgt. Jerry Carlsen and Laguna Hills resident Dorothy England 
were sent to Mission Hospital Regional Medical Center in Mission Viejo, treated 
for minor bruises and cuts, then released shortly after the accident, which 
occurred at the busy intersection of Alicia and Moulton parkways at 8 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 "They both got off with bumps and bruises," said sheriff's spokesman Lt. Dan 
Martini."They're going to be fine." 
</P>
<P>
 Carlsen, who is assigned to the city of Mission Viejo, was on his way to an 
accident scene when the collision took place. 
</P>
<P>
 As routinely occurs when a sheriff's vehicle is involved in an accident, the 
California Highway Patrol has been asked to investigate. 
</P>
<P>
 CHP spokesman Bruce Lian said initial reports indicate that England may have 
run a red light and hit the patrol car on the passenger side. 
</P>
<P>
 However, "our reports are still very preliminary," Lian said. "We're still 
looking into the cause of the accident." FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</TEXT>
