March 16, 1994, Wednesday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 2; Column 1; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
215 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: HUNTINGTON BEACH; POLICE ROUSE SUSPECT AFTER CAR CHASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FERNANDO ROMERO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A man suspected of stealing a car was arrested early Tuesday after SWAT team 
members had to rouse him after a car chase that began in Hawthorne, police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Police Lt. Patrick Gildea said he doesn't know if the suspect, Michael R. 
Randall, 36, fell asleep when he stopped the car on the 18000 block of 
Patterson Lane about 4 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Gildea said Randall refused to step out of the car or even to speak to 
pursuing officers.Assuming the suspect had a weapon, the officers summoned the 
SWAT team, which had no luck communicating with the suspect either, the 
lieutenant said. 
</P>
<P>
 "We thought the guy was unconscious or something because we didn't get a 
response," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 The SWAT team threw two "flash" grenades at the car, hoping to get the 
suspect's attention, Gildea said. Randall finally opened the passenger door for 
the officers and he was arrested on suspicion of auto theft, evading arrest and 
drunk driving, he said. 
</P>
<P>
 According to the CHP, the car chase started in Hawthorne, went through West 
Los Angeles and the South Bay before entering Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
 The car had been reported stolen in Huntington Beach on Feb. 21, Gildea said. 
</P>
<P>
 Randall was taken to Pacifica Community Hospital for evaluation and later 
booked at the Huntington Beach city jail, he said.FERNANDO ROMERO 
</P>
</TEXT>
